The article discusses the President's statement on the first anniversary of the Tribal Law and Order Act. The Act aims to address the high rates of violent crime experienced by American Indians and Alaska Natives. The President highlights the progress made in the past year, including increased sentencing authority for tribes, stronger rights for defendants, improved services for victims, efforts to combat alcohol and drug abuse, and better training for handling domestic violence and sex crimes. The government has also worked on expanding recruitment and retention of Bureau of Indian Affairs and tribal officers, as well as providing better access to criminal databases. The President emphasizes the importance of addressing these issues and promises to continue strengthening the government's relationship with Indian Country.